      <details>
        <summary><strong>1. COMPLAINT: SKIN LESION/RASH</strong></summary>
        <ol>











        </ol>

        <h4>Skin Lesion/Rash</h4>

        <ul>
          <li>S: Site (Location of skin lesion/rash)</li>
          <ul>
            <li> <strong>Scalp</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Seborrheic dermatitis</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Tinea capitis</li>
                <li>Folliculitis</li>
                <li>Alopecia areata</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Face</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Acne vulgaris</li>
                <li>Rosacea</li>
                <li>Perioral dermatitis</li>
                <li>Melasma</li>
                <li>Cold sores (Herpes simplex)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Lips</strong> </li>
            <ul>
              <li>Cold sores (Herpes simplex)</li>
              <li>Angular cheilitis</li>
              <li>Actinic cheilitis</li>
              <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
              <li>Impetigo</li>
            </ul>
            <li> <strong>Neck</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Lichen simplex chronicus</li>
                <li>Atopic dermatitis</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Chest</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Acne vulgaris</li>
                <li>Shingles (Herpes zoster)</li>
                <li>Pityriasis rosea</li>
                <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Back</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Acne vulgaris</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Folliculitis</li>
                <li>Shingles (Herpes zoster)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Abdomen</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Pityriasis rosea</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                <li>Shingles (Herpes zoster)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Groin</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Tinea cruris (jock itch)</li>
                <li>Intertrigo</li>
                <li>Inverse psoriasis</li>
                <li>Hidradenitis suppurativa</li>
                <li>Candidiasis</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Genital Area</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Balanitis</li>
                <li>Genital herpes</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Scabies</li>
                <li>Lichen sclerosus</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Buttocks</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Hidradenitis suppurativa</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Folliculitis</li>
                <li>Intertrigo</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Hands</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Contact dermatitis</li>
                <li>Dyshidrotic eczema</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Scabies</li>
                <li>Warts</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Feet</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Athlete's foot (Tinea pedis)</li>
                <li>Plantar warts</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Calluses</li>
                <li>Dyshidrotic eczema</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong>Nails</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Onychomycosis</li>
                <li>Psoriasis</li>
                <li>Lichen planus</li>
                <li>Paronychia</li>
                <li>Trachyonychia</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li> <strong></strong><br>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <li>O: Onset (rapid or chronic)</li>
          <li>D: Duration (Character and Type, e.g., macule, papule, vesicle)</li>
          <li>A: Aggravating factors (Accompanying symptoms)</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Allergens</li>
            <li>time of day</li>
            <li>place of stay</li>
            <li>bracelets</li>
            <li>rings</li>
            <li>cloth washing</li>
            <li>sun light</li>
            <li>water</li>
          </ul>
        </ul>

        <p><br>
        </p>

        <ul>
          <ul>
          </ul>
        </ul>

        <ul>
          <ul>
          </ul>
          <li>C: Character/Type </li>
          <ul>
            <li>papule</li>
            <li>Macule</li>
            <li>Papule</li>
            <li>Vesicle</li>
            <li>Pustule</li>
            <li>Nodule</li>
            <li>Cyst</li>
            <li>Wheal</li>
            <li>Ulcus</li>
          </ul>
          <li>R: Radiation (What improves it)</li>
          <li>A: Associated symptoms (What worsens it)</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Discharge</li>
            <li>itching</li>
            <li>Fever/ Flu</li>
            <li>Headache</li>
            <li>Fatigue</li>
            <li>Body aches</li>
            <li>R/o Cancer</li>
            <li>Weight loss</li>
            <li>Loss of appetite</li>
            <li>Anemia S/s</li>
            <li>Any lumps and</li>
            <li>bumps</li>
          </ul>
          <li>P: Progression (How it's changed)</li>
          <ul>
            <li>site</li>
            <li>size</li>
            <li>shape</li>
            <li>colour</li>
            <li><br>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <li>P: pattern</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Flat</li>
            <li>Raised</li>
          </ul>
          <li>R: R - for future expansions</li>
          <li>E: Effect on life (Radiation, spread)</li>
          <li>S: scale of zero to 10</li>
        </ul>

      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary><strong>2. COMPLAINT: LYMPH NODE SWELLING</strong></summary>
        <p class="derma">(Follow similar structure as above for lymph node swelling)</p>
        <h4>Lymph Node Swelling</h4>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Site:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
            Location of lymph node swelling
            <ul>
              <li>Localized or generalized</li>
              <li>Unilateral or bilateral</li>
              <li>Specific groups involved (cervical, axillary, inguinal, etc.)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Onset:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Gradual (chronic infections, malignancies)</li>
              <li>Sudden (acute infections, trauma)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Duration:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Short duration with pain = Inflammatory</li>
              <li>Intermediate duration without pain = Malignant</li>
              <li>Long duration with mild pain = Chronic inflammation</li>
              <li>Long duration without pain = Benign</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Progression:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Rapidly progressive (inflammatory, acute infections)</li>
              <li>Slowly progressive (malignancies, chronic infections)</li>
              <li>Static (benign conditions)</li>
              <li>Regression (with or without treatment)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Associated Symptoms:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Constitutional: Fever, night sweats, weight loss, fatigue</li>
              <li>Skin changes: Rash, ulceration, erythema, scaling</li>
              <li>Infection: Recent skin infections, dental infections, STIs</li>
              <li>Malignancy: Unexplained weight loss, night sweats, persistent
                fever</li>
              <li>Autoimmune: Joint pain, rash, photosensitivity</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Secondary Changes:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Skin changes over the node: Erythema, warmth, ulceration</li>
              <li>Fixation to skin or deeper structures</li>
              <li>Sinus or fistula formation</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Recurrence:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>History of previous lymph node swelling</li>
              <li>Response to previous treatments</li>
              <li>Recurrence after treatment</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Systemic Review:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Fever, chills, night sweats</li>
              <li>Weight loss, loss of appetite</li>
              <li>Fatigue, malaise</li>
              <li>Bone pain, joint pain</li>
              <li>Abdominal pain or fullness (splenomegaly)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
  
      </details>
      
